10190010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>Database</article>@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10190020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A '''database''' is a [[structure]]d collection of records or [[data]].@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10190030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A [[computer]] database relies upon [[software]] to organize the storage of data.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10190040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The software models the database structure in what are known as [[database model]]s.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10190050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The model in most common use today is the [[relational model]].@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10190060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Other models such as the [[hierarchical model]] and the [[network model]] use a more explicit representation of relationships (see below for explanation of the various database models).@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10190070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Database management systems (DBMS) are the software used to organize and maintain the database.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10190080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These are categorized according to the [[database model]] that they support.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10190090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The model tends to determine the query languages that are available to access the database.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10190100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A great deal of the internal engineering of a DBMS, however, is independent of the data model, and is concerned with managing factors such as performance, concurrency, integrity, and recovery from [[hardware failure]]s.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10190110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In these areas there are large differences between products.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10190120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==History==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10190130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The earliest known use of the term '''''data base''''' was in November 1963, when the [[System Development Corporation]] sponsored a symposium under the title ''Development and Management of a Computer-centered Data Base''.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10190140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@'''Database''' as a single word became common in Europe in the early 1970s and by the end of the decade it was being used in major American newspapers.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10190150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(The abbreviation DB, however, survives.)@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10190160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The first database management systems were developed in the 1960s.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10190170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A pioneer in the field was [[Charles Bachman]].@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10190180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Bachman's early papers show that his aim was to make more effective use of the new direct access storage devices becoming available: until then, data processing had been based on [[punch card|punched cards]] and [[magnetic tape]], so that serial processing was the dominant activity.@1@44@@oe@30-11-2008
10190190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Two key [[data model]]s arose at this time: [[CODASYL]] developed the [[network model]] based on Bachman's ideas, and (apparently independently) the [[hierarchical model]] was used in a system developed by [[North American Rockwell]] later adopted by [[IBM]] as the cornerstone of their [[Information Management System|IMS]] product.@1@46@@oe@30-11-2008
10190200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While IMS along with the CODASYL [[IDMS]] were the big, high visibility databases developed in the 1960s, several others were also born in that decade, some of which have a significant installed base today.@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10190210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Two worthy of mention are the [[Pick operating system|PICK]] and [[MUMPS]] databases, with the former developed originally as an operating system with an embedded database and the latter as a programming language and database for the development of healthcare systems.@1@40@@oe@30-11-2008
10190220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[relational model]] was proposed by [[Edgar F. Codd|E. F. Codd]] in 1970.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10190230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@He criticized existing models for confusing the abstract description of information structure with descriptions of physical access mechanisms.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10190240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For a long while, however, the relational model remained of academic interest only.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10190250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@While CODASYL products (IDMS) and network model products (IMS) were conceived as practical engineering solutions taking account of the technology as it existed at the time, the relational model took a much more theoretical perspective, arguing (correctly) that hardware and software technology would catch up in time.@1@47@@oe@30-11-2008
10190260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Among the first implementations were [[Michael Stonebraker]]'s [[Ingres (database)|Ingres]] at [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]], and the [[System R]] project at IBM.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10190270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Both of these were research prototypes, announced during 1976.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10190280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The first commercial products, [[Oracle database|Oracle]] and [[IBM DB2|DB2]], did not appear until around 1980.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10190290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The first successful database product for microcomputers was [[dBASE]] for the [[CP/M]] and [[PC-DOS]]/[[MS-DOS]] operating systems.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10190300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@During the 1980s, research activity focused on [[distributed database]] systems and [[database machine]]s.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10190310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another important theoretical idea was the [[Functional Data Model]], but apart from some specialized applications in genetics, molecular biology, and fraud investigation, the world took little notice.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10190320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the 1990s, attention shifted to [[OODB|object-oriented databases]].@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10190330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These had some success in fields where it was necessary to handle more complex data than relational systems could easily cope with, such as [[spatial database]]s, engineering data (including software [[Software repository|repositories]]), and multimedia data.@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10190340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some of these ideas were adopted by the relational vendors, who integrated new features into their products as a result.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10190350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The 1990s also saw the spread of [[Open Source]] databases, such as [[PostgreSQL]] and [[MySQL]].@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10190360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the 2000s, the fashionable area for innovation is the [[XML database]].@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10190370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As with object databases, this has spawned a new collection of start-up companies, but at the same time the key ideas are being integrated into the established relational products.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10190380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[XML databases]] aim to remove the traditional divide between documents and data, allowing all of an organization's information resources to be held in one place, whether they are highly structured or not.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10190390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Database models==@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10190400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Various techniques are used to model data structure.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10190410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Most database systems are built around one particular data model, although it is increasingly common for products to offer support for more than one model.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10190420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For any one [[logical model]] various physical implementations may be possible, and most products will offer the user some level of control in tuning the [[physical implementation]], since the choices that are made have a significant effect on performance.@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10190430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Here are three examples:@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10190440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Hierarchical model===@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10190450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In a [[hierarchical model]], data is organized into an inverted tree-like structure, implying a multiple downward link in each node to describe the nesting, and a sort field to keep the records in a particular order in each same-level list.@1@40@@oe@30-11-2008
10190460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This structure arranges the various data elements in a hierarchy and helps to establish logical relationships among data elements of multiple files.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10190470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Each unit in the model is a record which is also known as a node.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10190480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In such a model, each record on one level can be related to multiple records on the next lower level.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10190490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A record that has subsidiary records is called a parent and the subsidiary records are called children.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10190500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Data elements in this model are well suited for one-to-many relationships with other data elements in the database.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10190510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This model is advantageous when the data elements are inherently hierarchical.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10190520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The disadvantage is that in order to prepare the database it becomes necessary to identify the requisite groups of files that are to be logically integrated.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10190530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hence, a hierarchical data model may not always be flexible enough to accommodate the dynamic needs of an organization.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10190540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Network model===@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10190550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[network model]] tends to store records with links to other records.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10190560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Each record in the database can have multiple parents, i.e., the relationships among data elements can have a many to many relationship.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10190570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Associations are tracked via "pointers".@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10190580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These pointers can be node numbers or disk addresses.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10190590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Most network databases tend to also include some form of hierarchical model.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10190600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Databases can be translated from hierarchical model to network and vice versa.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10190610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The main difference between the network model and hierarchical model is that in a network model, a child can have a number of parents whereas in a hierarchical model, a child can have only one parent.@1@36@@oe@30-11-2008
10190620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The network model provides greater advantage than the hierarchical model in that promotes greater flexibility and data accessibility, since records at a lower level can be accessed without accessing the records above them.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10190630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This model is more efficient than hierarchical model, easier to understand and can be applied to many real world problems that require routine transactions.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10190640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The disadvantages are that: It is a complex process to design and develop a network database; It has to be refined frequently; It requires that the relationships among all the records be defined before development starts, and changes often demand major programming efforts; Operation and maintenance of the network model is expensive and time consuming.@1@55@@oe@30-11-2008
10190650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples of database engines that have network model capabilities are [[RDM Embedded]] and [[RDM Server]].@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10190660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Relational model===@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10190670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The basic data structure of the relational model is a table where information about a particular entity (say, an employee) is represented in columns and rows.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10190680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The columns enumerate the various attributes of an entity (e.g. employee_name, address, phone_number).@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10190690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Rows (also called records) represent instances of an entity (e.g. specific employees).@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10190700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The "relation" in "relational database" comes from the mathematical notion of [[Relation (mathematics)|relations]] from the field of [[set theory]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10190710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A relation is a set of [[tuple]]s, so rows are sometimes called tuples.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10190720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@All tables in a relational database adhere to three basic rules.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10190730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The ordering of columns is immaterial@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10190740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Identical rows are not allowed in a table@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10190750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Each row has a single (separate) value for each of its columns (each tuple has an atomic value).@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10190760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If the same value occurs in two different records (from the same table or different tables) it can imply a relationship between those records.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10190770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Relationships between records are often categorized by their [[Cardinality (data modeling)|cardinality]] (1:1, (0), 1:M, M:M).@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10190780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Tables can have a designated column or set of columns that act as a "key" to select rows from that table with the same or similar key values.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10190790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A "primary key" is a key that has a unique value for each row in the table.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10190800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Keys are commonly used to join or combine data from two or more tables.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10190810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, an ''employee'' table may contain a column named ''address'' which contains a value that matches the key of an ''address'' table.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10190820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Keys are also critical in the creation of indexes, which facilitate fast retrieval of data from large tables.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10190830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It is not necessary to define all the keys in advance; a column can be used as a key even if it was not originally intended to be one.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10190840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Relational operations====@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10190850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Users (or programs) request data from a relational database by sending it a [[query]] that is written in a special language, usually a dialect of [[SQL]].@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10190860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Although SQL was originally intended for end-users, it is much more common for SQL queries to be embedded into software that provides an easier user interface.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10190870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Many web applications, such as [[Wikipedia]], perform SQL queries when generating pages.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10190880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In response to a query, the database returns a result set, which is the list of rows constituting the answer.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10190890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The simplest query is just to return all the rows from a table, but more often, the rows are filtered in some way to return just the answer wanted.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10190900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Often, data from multiple tables are combined into one, by doing a [[Join (SQL)|join]].@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10190910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There are a number of relational operations in addition to join.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10190920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Normal forms====@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10190930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Relations are classified based upon the types of anomalies to which they're vulnerable.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10190940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A database that's in the first normal form is vulnerable to all types of anomalies, while a database that's in the domain/key normal form has no modification anomalies.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10190950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Normal forms are hierarchical in nature.@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10190960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@That is, the lowest level is the first normal form, and the database cannot meet the requirements for higher level normal forms without first having met all the requirements of the lesser normal form.@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10190970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Database Management Systems==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10190980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Relational database management systems===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10190990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An RDBMS implements the features of the relational model outlined above.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10191000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In this context, [[Christopher J. Date|Date]]'s '''Information Principle''' states:@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10191010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<blockquote> The entire information content of the database is represented in one and only one way.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10191020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Namely as explicit values in column positions (attributes) and rows in relations ([[tuple]]s) Therefore, there are no explicit pointers between related tables.</blockquote>@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10191030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Post-relational database models===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10191040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Several products have been identified as [[post-relational]] because the data model incorporates [[relations]] but is not constrained by the Information Principle, requiring that all information is represented by [[data values]] in relations.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10191050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Products using a post-relational data model typically employ a model that actually pre-dates the [[relational model]].@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10191060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These might be identified as a [[directed graph]] with [[tree data structure|trees]] on the [[data structure|nodes]].@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10191070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Examples of models that could be classified as post-relational are [[Pick operating system|PICK]] aka [[Multidimensional database|MultiValue]], and [[MUMPS]].@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10191080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Object database models===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10191090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In recent years, the [[object-oriented]] paradigm has been applied to database technology, creating a new programming model known as [[object database]]s.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10191100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These databases attempt to bring the database world and the application programming world closer together, in particular by ensuring that the database uses the same [[type system]] as the application program.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10191110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This aims to avoid the overhead (sometimes referred to as the ''[[Object-Relational impedance mismatch|impedance mismatch]]'') of converting information between its representation in the database (for example as rows in tables) and its representation in the application program (typically as objects).@1@40@@oe@30-11-2008
10191120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@At the same time, object databases attempt to introduce the key ideas of object programming, such as [[encapsulation]] and [[polymorphism (computer science)|polymorphism]], into the world of databases.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10191130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A variety of these ways have been tried for storing objects in a database.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10191140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some products have approached the problem from the application programming end, by making the objects manipulated by the program [[Persistence (computer science)|persistent]].@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10191150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This also typically requires the addition of some kind of query language, since conventional programming languages do not have the ability to find objects based on their information content.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10191160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Others have attacked the problem from the database end, by defining an object-oriented data model for the database, and defining a database programming language that allows full programming capabilities as well as traditional query facilities.@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10191170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==DBMS internals==@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10191180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Storage and physical database design===@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10191190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Database tables/indexes are typically stored in memory or on hard disk in one of many forms, ordered/unordered [[flat file database|flat files]], [[ISAM]], [[heap (data structure)|heaps]], [[hash table|hash buckets]] or [[B+ tree]]s.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10191200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@These have various advantages and disadvantages discussed further in the main article on this topic.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10191210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The most commonly used are B+ trees and ISAM.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10191220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Other important design choices relate to the clustering of data by category (such as grouping data by month, or location), creating pre-computed views known as materialized views, partitioning data by range or hash.@1@33@@oe@30-11-2008
10191230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As well memory management and storage topology can be important design choices for database designers.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10191240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Just as normalization is used to reduce storage requirements and improve the extensibility of the database, conversely denormalization is often used to reduce join complexity and reduce execution time for queries.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10191250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Indexing====@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10191260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@All of these databases can take advantage of [[Index (database)|indexing]] to increase their speed.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10191270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This technology has advanced tremendously since its early uses in the 1960s and 1970s.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10191280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The most common kind of index is a sorted list of the contents of some particular table column, with pointers to the row associated with the value.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10191290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An index allows a set of table rows matching some criterion to be located quickly.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10191300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Typically, indexes are also stored in the various forms of data-structure mentioned above (such as [[B-tree]]s, [[hash table|hash]]es, and [[linked lists]]).@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10191310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Usually, a specific technique is chosen by the database designer to increase efficiency in the particular case of the type of index required.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10191320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Relational DBMS's have the advantage that indexes can be created or dropped without changing existing applications making use of it.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10191330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The database chooses between many different strategies based on which one it estimates will run the fastest.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10191340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In other words, indexes are transparent to the application or end-user querying the database; while they affect performance, any SQL command will run with or without index to compute the result of an [[SQL]] statement.@1@35@@oe@30-11-2008
10191350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The RDBMS will produce a plan of how to execute the query, which is generated by analyzing the run times of the different algorithms and selecting the quickest.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10191360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Some of the key algorithms that deal with [[join (SQL)|joins]] are [[nested loop join]], [[sort-merge join]] and [[hash join]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10191370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Which of these is chosen depends on whether an index exists, what type it is, and its [[Cardinality (SQL statements)|cardinality]].@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10191380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An index speeds up access to data, but it has disadvantages as well.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10191390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@First, every index increases the amount of storage on the hard drive necessary for the database file, and second, the index must be updated each time the data are altered, and this costs time.@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10191400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(Thus an index saves time in the reading of data, but it costs time in entering and altering data.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10191410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It thus depends on the use to which the data are to be put whether an index is on the whole a net plus or minus in the quest for efficiency.)@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10191420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A special case of an index is a primary index, or primary key, which is distinguished in that the primary index must ensure a unique reference to a record.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10191430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Often, for this purpose one simply uses a running index number (ID number).@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10191440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Primary indexes play a significant role in relational databases, and they can speed up access to data considerably.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10191450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Transactions and concurrency===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10191460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In addition to their data model, most practical databases ("transactional databases") attempt to enforce a [[database transaction]] .@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10191470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Ideally, the database software should enforce the [[ACID]] rules, summarized here:@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10191480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Atomicity]]: Either all the tasks in a transaction must be done, or none of them.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10191490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The transaction must be completed, or else it must be undone (rolled back).@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10191500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Database consistency|Consistency]]: Every transaction must preserve the integrity constraints — the declared consistency rules — of the database.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10191510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It cannot place the data in a contradictory state.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10191520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Isolation]]: Two simultaneous transactions cannot interfere with one another.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10191530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Intermediate results within a transaction are not visible to other transactions.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10191540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Durability (computer science)|Durability]]: Completed transactions cannot be aborted later or their results discarded.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10191550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@They must persist through (for instance) restarts of the DBMS after crashes@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10191560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In practice, many DBMS's allow most of these rules to be selectively relaxed for better performance.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10191570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Concurrency control]] is a method used to ensure that transactions are executed in a safe manner and follow the ACID rules.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10191580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The DBMS must be able to ensure that only [[serializability|serializable]], [[serializability#correctness - recoverability|recoverable]] schedules are allowed, and that no actions of committed transactions are lost while undoing aborted transactions .@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10191590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Replication===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10191600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Replication of databases is closely related to transactions.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10191610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If a database can log its individual actions, it is possible to create a duplicate of the data in real time.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10191620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The duplicate can be used to improve performance or availability of the whole database system.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10191630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Common replication concepts include:@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10191640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Master/Slave Replication: All write requests are performed on the master and then replicated to the slaves@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10191650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Quorum: The result of Read and Write requests are calculated by querying a "majority" of replicas.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10191660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Multimaster: Two or more replicas sync each other via a transaction identifier.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10191670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Parallel synchronous replication of databases enables transactions to be replicated on multiple servers simultaneously, which provides a method for backup and security as well as data availability.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10191680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Security===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10191690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Database security]] denotes the system, processes, and procedures that protect a database from unintended activity.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10191700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Security is usually enforced through '''access control''', '''auditing''', and '''encryption'''.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10191710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Access control ensures and restricts who can connect and what can be done to the database.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10191720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Auditing logs what action or change has been performed, when and by who.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10191730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Encryption: Since security has become a major issue in recent years, many commercial database vendors provide built-in encryption mechanism.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10191740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Data is encoded natively into the tables and deciphered "on the fly" when a query comes in. Connections can also be secured and encrypted if required using DSA, MD5, SSL or legacy encryption standard.@1@34@@oe@30-11-2008
10191750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Enforcing security is one of the major tasks of the DBA.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10191760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the United Kingdom, legislation protecting the public from unauthorized disclosure of personal information held on databases falls under the Office of the Information Commissioner.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10191770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@United Kingdom based organizations holding personal data in electronic format (databases for example) are required to register with the Data Commissioner.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10191780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Locking===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10191790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Lock (computer science)|Locking]] is how the database handle multiple concurent operations.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10191800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is the way how concurency and some form of basic intergrity is managed within the database system.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10191810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Such locks can be applied on a row level, or on other levels like page (a basic data block), extend (multiple array of pages) or even an entire table.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10191820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This helps maintain the integrity of the data by ensuring that only one process at a time can modify the '''same''' data.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10191830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Unlike a basic filesystem files or folders, where only one lock at the time can be set, restricting the usage to one process only.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10191840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A database can set and hold mutiples locks at the same time on the different level of the physical data structure.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10191850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@How locks are set, last is determined by the database engine locking scheme based on the submitted SQL or transactions by the users.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10191860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Generaly speaking no activity on the database should be translated by no or very light locking.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10191870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For most DBMS systems existing on the market, locks are generaly '''shared''' or '''exclusive'''.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10191880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Exclusive locks mean that no other lock can acquire the current data object as long as the exclusive lock lasts.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10191890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Exclusive locks are usually set while the database needs to change data, like during an UPDATE or DELETE operation.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10191900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Shared locks can take ownership one from the other of the current data structure.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10191910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Shared locks are usually used while the database is reading data, during a SELECT operation.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10191920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The number, nature of locks and time the lock holds a data block can have a huge impact on the database performances.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10191930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Bad locking can lead to desastrous performance response (usually the result of poor SQL requests, or inadequate database physical structure)@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10191940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Default locking behavior is enforced by the '''isolation level''' of the dataserver.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10191950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Changing the isolation level will affect how shared or exclusive locks must be set on the data for the entire database system.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10191960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Default isolation is generaly 1, where data can not be read while it is modfied, forbiding to return "ghost data" to end user.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10191970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@At some point intensive or inappropriate exclusive locking, can lead to the "dead lock" situation between two locks.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10191980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Where none of the locks can be released because they try to acquire ressources mutually from each other.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10191990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The Database has a fail safe mecanism and will automaticly "sacrifice" one of the locks releasing the ressource.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10192000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Doing so processes or transactions involved in the "dead lock" will be rolled back.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10192010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Databases can also be locked for other reasons, like access restrictions for given levels of user.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10192020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Databases are also locked for routine database maintenance, which prevents changes being made during the maintenance.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10192030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@See [http://publib.boulder.ibm.com/infocenter/rbhelp/v6r3/index.jsp?topic=/com.ibm.redbrick.doc6.3/wag/wag80.htm IBM] for more detail.)@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10192040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Architecture===@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10192050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Depending on the intended use, there are a number of database architectures in use.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10192060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Many databases use a combination of strategies.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10192070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@On-line Transaction Processing systems (OLTP) often use a row-oriented datastore architecture, while data-warehouse and other retrieval-focused applications like [[Google]]'s [[BigTable]], or bibliographic database(library catalogue) systems may use a column-oriented datastore architecture.@1@31@@oe@30-11-2008
10192080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Document-Oriented, XML, Knowledgebases, as well as frame databases and rdf-stores (aka Triple-Stores), may also use a combination of these architectures in their implementation.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10192090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Finally it should be noted that not all database have or need a database 'schema' (so called schema-less databases).@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10192100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Applications of databases==@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
