10200010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>Cluster analysis</article>@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10200020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@'''Clustering''' is the [[Statistical classification|classification]] of objects into different groups, or more precisely, the [[partition of a set|partitioning]] of a [[data set]] into [[subset]]s (clusters), so that the data in each subset (ideally) share some common trait - often proximity according to some defined [[metric (mathematics)|distance measure]].@1@47@@oe@30-11-2008
10200030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Data clustering is a common technique for [[statistics|statistical]] [[data analysis]], which is used in many fields, including [[machine learning]], [[data mining]], [[pattern recognition]], [[image analysis]] and [[bioinformatics]].@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10200040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The computational task of classifying the data set into ''k'' clusters is often referred to as '''''k''-clustering'''''.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10200050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Besides the term ''data clustering'' (or just ''clustering''), there are a number of terms with similar meanings, including ''cluster analysis'', ''automatic classification'', ''numerical taxonomy'', ''botryology'' and ''typological analysis''.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10200060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Types of clustering ==@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10200070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Data clustering algorithms can be [[hierarchical]].@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10200080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hierarchical algorithms find successive clusters using previously established clusters.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10200090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hierarchical algorithms can be agglomerative ("bottom-up") or divisive ("top-down").@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10200100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Agglomerative algorithms begin with each element as a separate cluster and merge them into successively larger clusters.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10200110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Divisive algorithms begin with the whole set and proceed to divide it into successively smaller clusters.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10200120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[partition of a set|Partitional]] algorithms typically determine all clusters at once, but can also be used as divisive algorithms in the [[hierarchical]] clustering.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10200130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@''Two-way clustering'', ''co-clustering'' or [[biclustering]] are clustering methods where not only the objects are clustered but also the features of the objects, i.e., if the data is represented in a [[data matrix (statistics)|data matrix]], the rows and columns are clustered simultaneously.@1@41@@oe@30-11-2008
10200140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another important distinction is whether the clustering uses symmetric or asymmetric distances.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10200150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A property of [[Euclidean space]] is that distances are symmetric (the distance from object'' A'' to ''B'' is the same as the distance from ''B'' to ''A'').@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10200160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In other applications (e.g., sequence-alignment methods, see Prinzie & Van den Poel (2006)), this is not the case.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Distance measure ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10200180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@An important step in any clustering is to select a [[Distance|distance measure]], which will determine how the ''similarity'' of two elements is calculated.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10200190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This will influence the shape of the clusters, as some elements may be close to one another according to one distance and further away according to another.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10200200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, in a 2-dimensional space, the distance between the point (x=1, y=0) and the origin (x=0, y=0) is always 1 according to the usual norms, but the distance between the point (x=1, y=1) and the origin can be 2,<math>\\sqrt 2</math> or 1 if you take respectively the 1-norm, 2-norm or infinity-norm distance.@1@53@@oe@30-11-2008
10200210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Common distance functions:@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10200220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The [[Euclidean distance]] (also called distance [[as the crow flies]] or 2-norm distance).@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10200230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A review of cluster analysis in health psychology research found that the most common distance measure in published studies in that research area is the Euclidean distance or the squared Euclidean distance.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10200240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The [[Manhattan distance]] (also called taxicab norm or 1-norm)@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10200250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The [[Maximum_norm|maximum norm]]@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10200260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The [[Mahalanobis distance]] corrects data for different scales and correlations in the variables@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10200270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The angle between two vectors can be used as a distance measure when clustering high dimensional data.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@See [[Inner product space]].@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10200290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The [[Hamming distance]] (sometimes edit distance) measures the minimum number of substitutions required to change one member into another.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10200300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Hierarchical clustering==@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10200310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Creating clusters===@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10200320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Hierarchical clustering builds (agglomerative), or breaks up (divisive), a hierarchy of clusters.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10200330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The traditional representation of this hierarchy is a [[tree data structure|tree]] (called a [[dendrogram]]), with individual elements at one end and a single cluster containing every element at the other.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10200340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Agglomerative algorithms begin at the top of the tree, whereas divisive algorithms begin at the root.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10200350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@(In the figure, the arrows indicate an agglomerative clustering.)@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10200360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Cutting the tree at a given height will give a clustering at a selected precision.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10200370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In the following example, cutting after the second row will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e} {f}.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Cutting after the third row will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e f}, which is a coarser clustering, with a smaller number of larger clusters.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10200390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===Agglomerative hierarchical clustering===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10200400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, suppose this data is to be clustered, and the [[euclidean distance]] is the [[Metric (mathematics)|distance metric]].@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The hierarchical clustering [[dendrogram]] would be as such:@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10200420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This method builds the hierarchy from the individual elements by progressively merging clusters.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10200430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In our example, we have six elements {a} {b} {c} {d} {e} and {f}.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10200440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The first step is to determine which elements to merge in a cluster.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10200450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Usually, we want to take the two closest elements, according to the chosen distance.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10200460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Optionally, one can also construct a [[distance matrix]] at this stage, where the number in the ''i''-th row ''j''-th column is the distance between the ''i''-th and ''j''-th elements.@1@29@@oe@30-11-2008
10200470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Then, as clustering progresses, rows and columns are merged as the clusters are merged and the distances updated.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is a common way to implement this type of clustering, and has the benefit of caching distances between clusters.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10200490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A simple agglomerative clustering algorithm is described in the [[single linkage clustering]] page; it can easily be adapted to different types of linkage (see below).@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10200500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Suppose we have merged the two closest elements ''b'' and ''c'', we now have the following clusters {''a''}, {''b'', ''c''}, {''d''}, {''e''} and {''f''}, and want to merge them further.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10200510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@To do that, we need to take the distance between {a} and {b c}, and therefore define the distance between two clusters.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10200520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Usually the distance between two clusters <math>\\mathcal{A}</math> and <math>\\mathcal{B}</math> is one of the following:@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10200530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The maximum distance between elements of each cluster (also called complete linkage clustering):@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10200540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@::<math> \\max \\{\\, d(x,y) : x \\in \\mathcal{A},\\, y \\in \\mathcal{B}\\,\\} </math>@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10200550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The minimum distance between elements of each cluster (also called [[single linkage clustering]]):@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10200560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@::<math> \\min \\{\\, d(x,y) : x \\in \\mathcal{A},\\, y \\in \\mathcal{B} \\,\\} </math>@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10200570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The mean distance between elements of each cluster (also called average linkage clustering, used e.g. in [[UPGMA]]):@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@::<math> {1 \\over {|\\mathcal{A}|\\cdot|\\mathcal{B}|}}\\sum_{x \\in \\mathcal{A}}\\sum_{ y \\in \\mathcal{B}} d(x,y) </math>@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10200590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The sum of all intra-cluster variance@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10200600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The increase in variance for the cluster being merged ([[Ward's criterion]])@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10200610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The probability that candidate clusters spawn from the same distribution function (V-linkage)@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10200620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Each agglomeration occurs at a greater distance between clusters than the previous agglomeration, and one can decide to stop clustering either when the clusters are too far apart to be merged (distance criterion) or when there is a sufficiently small number of clusters (number criterion).@1@45@@oe@30-11-2008
10200630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Concept clustering ===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10200640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Another variation of the agglomerative clustering approach is [[conceptual clustering]].@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10200650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Partitional clustering==@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10200660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@===''K''-means and derivatives===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10200670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====''K''-means clustering====@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10200680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[K-means algorithm|''K''-means algorithm]] assigns each point to the cluster whose center (also called centroid) is nearest.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10200690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The center is the average of all the points in the cluster — that is, its coordinates are the arithmetic mean for each dimension separately over all the points in the cluster...@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10200700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:''Example:'' The data set has three dimensions and the cluster has two points: ''X'' = (''x''<sub>1</sub>, ''x''<sub>2</sub>, ''x''<sub>3</sub>) and ''Y'' = (''y''<sub>1</sub>, ''y''<sub>2</sub>, ''y''<sub>3</sub>).@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10200710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Then the centroid ''Z'' becomes ''Z'' = (''z''<sub>1</sub>, ''z''<sub>2</sub>, ''z''<sub>3</sub>), where ''z''<sub>1</sub> = (''x''<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;+&nbsp;''y''<sub>1</sub>)/2 and ''z''<sub>2</sub> = (''x''<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;+&nbsp;''y''<sub>2</sub>)/2 and ''z''<sub>3</sub> = (''x''<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;+&nbsp;''y''<sub>3</sub>)/2.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10200720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The algorithm steps are (J. MacQueen, 1967):@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10200730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Choose the number of clusters, ''k''.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10200740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Randomly generate ''k'' clusters and determine the cluster centers, or directly generate ''k'' random points as cluster centers.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10200750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Assign each point to the nearest cluster center.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10200760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Recompute the new cluster centers.@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10200770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Repeat the two previous steps until some convergence criterion is met (usually that the assignment hasn't changed).@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The main advantages of this algorithm are its simplicity and speed which allows it to run on large datasets.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10200790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Its disadvantage is that it does not yield the same result with each run, since the resulting clusters depend on the initial random assignments.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10200800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It minimizes intra-cluster variance, but does not ensure that the result has a global minimum of variance.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10200810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====Fuzzy ''c''-means clustering====@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10200820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[fuzzy clustering]], each point has a degree of belonging to clusters, as in [[fuzzy logic]], rather than belonging completely to just one cluster.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10200830@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus, points on the edge of a cluster, may be ''in the cluster'' to a lesser degree than points in the center of cluster.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10200840@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For each point ''x'' we have a coefficient giving the degree of being in the ''k''th cluster <math>u_k(x)</math>.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200850@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Usually, the sum of those coefficients is defined to be 1:@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10200860@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:<math> \\forall x \\sum_{k=1}^{\\mathrm{num.}\\ \\mathrm{clusters}} u_k(x) \\ =1.</math>@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10200870@unknown@formal@none@1@S@With fuzzy ''c''-means, the centroid of a cluster is the mean of all points, weighted by their degree of belonging to the cluster:@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10200880@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:<math>\\mathrm{center}_k = {{\\sum_x u_k(x)^m x} \\over {\\sum_x u_k(x)^m}}.</math>@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10200890@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The degree of belonging is related to the inverse of the distance to the cluster@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10200900@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:<math>u_k(x) = {1 \\over d(\\mathrm{center}_k,x)},</math>@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10200910@unknown@formal@none@1@S@then the coefficients are normalized and fuzzyfied with a real parameter <math>m>1</math> so that their sum is 1.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200920@unknown@formal@none@1@S@So@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10200930@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:<math>u_k(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sum_j \\left(\\frac{d(\\mathrm{center}_k,x)}{d(\\mathrm{center}_j,x)}\\right)^{2/(m-1)}}.</math>@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10200940@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For ''m'' equal to 2, this is equivalent to normalising the coefficient linearly to make their sum 1.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10200950@unknown@formal@none@1@S@When ''m'' is close to 1, then cluster center closest to the point is given much more weight than the others, and the algorithm is similar to ''k''-means.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10200960@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The fuzzy ''c''-means algorithm is very similar to the ''k''-means algorithm:@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10200970@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Choose a number of clusters.@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10200980@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Assign randomly to each point coefficients for being in the clusters.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10200990@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Repeat until the algorithm has converged (that is, the coefficients' change between two iterations is no more than <math>\\epsilon</math>, the given sensitivity threshold) :@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10201000@unknown@formal@none@1@S@** Compute the centroid for each cluster, using the formula above.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10201010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@** For each point, compute its coefficients of being in the clusters, using the formula above.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10201020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The algorithm minimizes intra-cluster variance as well, but has the same problems as ''k''-means, the minimum is a local minimum, and the results depend on the initial choice of weights.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10201030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The [[Expectation-maximization algorithm]] is a more statistically formalized method which includes some of these ideas: partial membership in classes.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10201040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It has better convergence properties and is in general preferred to fuzzy-c-means.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10201050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@====QT clustering algorithm====@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10201060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@QT (quality threshold) clustering (Heyer et al, 1999) is an alternative method of partitioning data, invented for gene clustering.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10201070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It requires more computing power than ''k''-means, but does not require specifying the number of clusters ''a priori'', and always returns the same result when run several times.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10201080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The algorithm is:@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10201090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* The user chooses a maximum diameter for clusters.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10201100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Build a candidate cluster for each point by including the closest point, the next closest, and so on, until the diameter of the cluster surpasses the threshold.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10201110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* Save the candidate cluster with the most points as the first true cluster, and remove all points in the cluster from further consideration.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10201120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Must clarify what happens if more than 1 cluster has the maximum number of points ?@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10201130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@* [[Recursion|Recurse]] with the reduced set of points.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10201140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The distance between a point and a group of points is computed using complete linkage, i.e. as the maximum distance from the point to any member of the group (see the "Agglomerative hierarchical clustering" section about distance between clusters).@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10201150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Locality-sensitive hashing ===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10201160@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Locality-sensitive hashing]] can be used for clustering.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10201170@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Feature space vectors are sets, and the metric used is the [[Jaccard distance]].@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10201180@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The feature space can be considered high-dimensional.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10201190@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The ''min-wise independent permutations'' LSH scheme (sometimes MinHash) is then used to put similar items into buckets.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10201200@unknown@formal@none@1@S@With just one set of hashing methods, there are only clusters of very similar elements.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10201210@unknown@formal@none@1@S@By seeding the hash functions several times (eg 20), it is possible to get bigger clusters.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10201220@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Graph-theoretic methods ===@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10201230@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Formal concept analysis]] is a technique for generating clusters of objects and attributes, given a [[bipartite graph]] representing the relations between the objects and attributes.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10201240@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Other methods for generating ''overlapping clusters'' (a [[Cover (topology)|cover]] rather than a [[partition of a set|partition]]) are discussed by Jardine and Sibson (1968) and Cole and Wishart (1970).@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10201250@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Elbow criterion ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10201260@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The elbow criterion is a common [[rule of thumb]] to determine what number of clusters should be chosen, for example for ''k''-means and agglomerative hierarchical clustering.@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10201270@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It should also be noted that the initial assignment of cluster seeds has bearing on the final model performance.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10201280@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Thus, it is appropriate to re-run the cluster analysis multiple times.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10201290@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The elbow criterion says that you should choose a number of clusters so that adding another cluster doesn't add sufficient information.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10201300@unknown@formal@none@1@S@More precisely, if you graph the percentage of variance explained by the clusters against the number of clusters, the first clusters will add much information (explain a lot of variance), but at some point the marginal gain will drop, giving an angle in the graph (the elbow).@1@47@@oe@30-11-2008
10201310@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This elbow cannot always be unambiguously identified.@1@7@@oe@30-11-2008
10201320@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Percentage of variance explained is the ratio of the between-group variance to the total variance.@1@15@@oe@30-11-2008
10201330@unknown@formal@none@1@S@On the following graph, the elbow is indicated by the red circle.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10201340@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The number of clusters chosen should therefore be 4.@1@9@@oe@30-11-2008
10201350@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Spectral clustering ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10201360@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Given a set of data points A, the [[similarity matrix]] may be defined as a matrix <math>S</math> where <math>S_{ij}</math> represents a measure of the similarity between points <math>i, j\\in A</math>.@1@30@@oe@30-11-2008
10201370@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Spectral clustering techniques make use of the [[Spectrum of a matrix|spectrum]] of the similarity matrix of the data to perform [[dimensionality reduction]] for clustering in fewer dimensions.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10201380@unknown@formal@none@1@S@One such technique is the ''[[Shi-Malik algorithm]]'', commonly used for [[segmentation (image processing)|image segmentation]].@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10201390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@It partitions points into two sets <math>(S_1,S_2)</math> based on the [[eigenvector]] <math>v</math> corresponding to the second-smallest [[eigenvalue]] of the [[Laplacian matrix]]@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10201400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:<math>L = I - D^{-1/2}SD^{-1/2}</math>@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10201410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@of <math>S</math>, where <math>D</math> is the diagonal matrix@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10201420@unknown@formal@none@1@S@:<math>D_{ii} = \\sum_{j} S_{ij}.</math>@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10201430@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This partitioning may be done in various ways, such as by taking the median <math>m</math> of the components in <math>v</math>, and placing all points whose component in <math>v</math> is greater than <math>m</math> in <math>S_1</math>, and the rest in <math>S_2</math>.@1@39@@oe@30-11-2008
10201440@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The algorithm can be used for hierarchical clustering by repeatedly partitioning the subsets in this fashion.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10201450@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A related algorithm is the ''[[Meila-Shi algorithm]]'', which takes the [[eigenvector]]s corresponding to the ''k'' largest [[eigenvalue]]s of the matrix <math>P = SD^{-1}</math> for some ''k'', and then invokes another (e.g. ''k''-means) to cluster points by their respective ''k'' components in these eigenvectors.@1@43@@oe@30-11-2008
10201460@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Applications==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10201470@unknown@formal@none@1@S@=== Biology ===@1@3@@oe@30-11-2008
10201480@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In [[biology]] '''clustering''' has many applications@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10201490@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*In imaging, data clustering may take different form based on the data dimensionality.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10201500@unknown@formal@none@1@S@For example, the [http://wiki.stat.ucla.edu/socr/index.php/SOCR_EduMaterials_Activities_2D_PointSegmentation_EM_Mixture SOCR EM Mixture model segmentation activity and applet] shows how to obtain point, region or volume classification using the online [[SOCR]] computational libraries.@1@27@@oe@30-11-2008
10201510@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*In the fields of [[plant]] and [[animal]] [[ecology]], clustering is used to describe and to make spatial and temporal comparisons of communities (assemblages) of organisms in heterogeneous environments; it is also used in [[Systematics|plant systematics]] to generate artificial [[Phylogeny|phylogenies]] or clusters of organisms (individuals) at the species, genus or higher level that share a number of attributes@1@57@@oe@30-11-2008
10201520@unknown@formal@none@1@S@*In computational biology and [[bioinformatics]]:@1@5@@oe@30-11-2008
10201530@unknown@formal@none@1@S@** In [[transcriptome|transcriptomics]], clustering is used to build groups of [[genes]] with related expression patterns (also known as coexpressed genes).@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10201540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Often such groups contain functionally related proteins, such as [[enzyme]]s for a specific [[metabolic pathway|pathway]], or genes that are co-regulated.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10201550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@High throughput experiments using [[expressed sequence tag]]s (ESTs) or [[DNA microarray]]s can be a powerful tool for [[genome annotation]], a general aspect of [[genomics]].@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
